							Well, as far as the ADA is concerned, any gaming company with more than 25 employees would have to hire qualified applicants who are disabled, for example in their Testing department or in their In-Game Customer Service department, so it would behoove any such companies worth their salt to make accessibility to the disabled an inherent design element of any games they develop, so that such employees can be readily accommodated.
